4","1295":"1295","Cir 1297":"1297","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1247":"1247","1357":"1357","1245":"1245","1453":"1453","about 1269":"about 1269","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Helston, Cornwall, England":"Helston, Cornwall, England","Godolphin, Cornwall, England":"Godolphin Cross, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Godolphin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish, English: locative name from Godolphin (Cornwall), recorded as  <i>Wulgholgan</i> in 1194."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Edward","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."],"variants":[{"name":"Edoardo","meanings":["From English.  See  <b>Edward</b> ."]},{"name":"Eudard","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]},{"name":"Eduardo","meanings":["From English.  See  <b>Edward</b> ."]},{"name":"Eideard","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Edward</b> ."]},{"name":"Édouard","meanings":["From English.  See  <b>Edward</b> ."]},{"name":"Edvard","meanings":["form of English <b>Edward</b> ."]},{"name":"Eduard","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]},{"name":"Duarte","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Edward de Godolphin II was born in 1270, in Helston, Cornwall, England, his father, Thomas de Godolphin II, was 25 and his mother, Claricia de Solgena, was 23. He married Christian de Prideaux in Helston, Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1349, in Cornwall, England, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1270–1349":"1270–1349","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1295–1349":"1295–1349","1297–1357":"1297–1357","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","Cir 1297":"1297","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1247":"1247","1357":"1357","1245":"1245","1453":"1453","about 1269":"umbes 1269","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Helston, Cornwall, England":"Helston, Cornwall, England","Godolphin, Cornwall, England":"Godolphin Cross, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1270–1349":"1270–1349","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1295–1349":"1295–1349","1297–1357":"1297–1357","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1247–Female":"1247–Kuollut","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","Cir 1297":"1297","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1247":"1247","1357":"1357","1245":"1245","1453":"1453","about 1269":"noin 1269","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Helston, Cornwall, England":"Helston, Cornwall, England","Godolphin, Cornwall, England":"Godolphin Cross, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1270–1349":"1270–1349","1274–Female":"1274–Décédée","1295–1349":"1295–1349","1297–1357":"1297–1357","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1247–Female":"1247–Décédée","1297":"1297","1274":